{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17471837","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17471837"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:52:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:52:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"876"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"876","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/876"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.09,0.77,0.02,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"876"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88494"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"876","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/876"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"876"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72697"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"564"},{"type":"tags","id":"1713"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3253"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3304"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15943"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43043"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44035"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88494","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/88494"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 14-year-old girl presents to the General Practice clinic with concerns that her periods have not started yet. She is accompanied by her mother, who reports that the girl has learning difficulties. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. She has a short stature (height below the third percentile for age), webbing of the neck, and a broad chest with widely spaced nipples.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying genetic abnormality?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Trisomy 21","Trisomy 18","45,X0","15q21.1 mutation","22q11.2 deletion"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of Turner syndrome, which is characterised by the karyotype \u003Cstrong\u003E45,X0\u003C/strong\u003E (partly or completely missing an X-chromosome). The clinical presentation includes primary amenorrhoea, short stature, webbed neck, and a broad chest with widely spaced nipples. These features strongly support the diagnosis of Turner syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003ETurner syndrome results from complete or partial absence of one X chromosome, leading to impaired ovarian development and deficiencies in oestrogen and progesterone secretion. Patients have a female phenotype but typically present with delayed puberty, primary amenorrhoea, and infertility due to \u0022streak gonads\u0022 (ovaries consisting mainly of connective tissue).\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrisomy 21\u003C/strong\u003E (Down syndrome) presents with different physical features including upward slanting of eyelids, epicanthal folds, low-set ears, transverse palmar crease, and joint hyperflexibility. Patients may have cardiac defects such as atrioventricular septal defects. While intellectual disability is common, the physical features described in this case are not consistent with Down syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrisomy 18\u003C/strong\u003E (Edward\u0027s syndrome) is characterised by severe intellectual disability, growth deficiency, clenched fists with overlapping fingers, congenital heart defects, and distinctive facial features. This condition is typically fatal within the first year of life, making it inconsistent with a 14-year-old presenting with primary amenorrhoea.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E15q21.1 mutation\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with Marfan syndrome, which presents with tall stature, long extremities, joint hypermobility, and cardiovascular complications such as aortic dissection. This is inconsistent with the short stature and other features described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E22q11.2 deletion\u003C/strong\u003E (DiGeorge syndrome) typically presents with cardiac anomalies, abnormal facies, thymic hypoplasia, cleft palate, and hypocalcaemia due to hypoparathyroidism. While learning difficulties can be present, the physical features described in this case are more consistent with Turner syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003EPatients with Turner syndrome usually have normal intelligence but may have specific neurocognitive deficits affecting visuospatial organisation, mathematics, and attention, which can lead to learning difficulties. They require lifelong monitoring for associated conditions including cardiovascular abnormalities (bicuspid aortic valve, coarctation of the aorta), renal anomalies, hypothyroidism, and osteoporosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Turner syndrome is characterised by complete or partial absence of one X chromosome (45,X0), resulting in primary amenorrhoea and characteristic physical features.","Clinical features of Turner syndrome include short stature, webbed neck, broad chest, primary amenorrhoea, and learning difficulties.","Patients with Turner syndrome require lifelong monitoring for associated cardiovascular, renal, and endocrine complications."],"references":["Gravholt CH, Viuff M, Just J, Sandahl K, Brun S, van der Velden J, et al. The Changing Face of Turner Syndrome. Endocrine Reviews. 2023;44(1):33-69. Available at: https://academic.oup.com/edrv/article/44/1/33/6607573","Kikkeri NS. Turner Syndrome. In: StatPearls [Online]. U.S. National Library of Medicine; 2021 [cited 2021 Jul 22]. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK554621/","Akhtar F. Down syndrome In: StatPearls [Online]. U.S. National Library of Medicine; 2021 [cited 2021 Jul 27]. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK526016/","Balasundaram P. Edward syndrome. In: StatPearls [Online]. U.S. National Library of Medicine; 2021 [cited 2021 Jul 27]. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK570597/","Lackey AE. DiGeorge syndrome. In: StatPearls [Online]. U.S. National Library of Medicine; 2021 [cited 2021 Jul 27]. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK549798/","Salik I. Marfan syndrome. In: StatPearls [Online]. U.S. National Library of Medicine; 2021 [cited 2021 Jul 27]. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537339/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72697"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"876"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72697","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/72697"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-05T09:14:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-05T09:14:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"876"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88494"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes